#compdef pino-pretty
# ============================================================================
# pino-pretty - Pino log line prettifier
#                CLI for development +
#                debugging
#                (TypeScript/Node, MIT)
#
# Author : James Sumners (jsumners) +
#           Matteo Collina + pinojs team
# Upstream: https://github.com/pinojs/pino-pretty
# npm pkg : pino-pretty
#
# `pino-pretty` is the canonical Node CLI
# for prettifying JSON log lines produced
# by the Pino structured logger. Reads JSON
# log lines from stdin (one per line) and
# emits a human-readable formatted version
# to stdout - the standard development
# workflow for Pino-using Node services.
#
# Pino's design philosophy: emit raw JSON
# in production (fast + log-aggregator-
# friendly) + pretty-print via pino-pretty
# only during development. This separation
# of concerns lets production keep zero-
# overhead JSON output while development
# gets readable logs.
#
# Architecture:
#   1. **Stdin pipeline mode** (cat
#      logs | pino-pretty)
#   2. **Configurable formatting** (colorize
#      + level position + message format
#      + timestamp translation + field
#      filtering)
#   3. **Config file support**
#     (.pino-prettyrc + pino-pretty.config
#     .cjs + JoyCon-style config
#     discovery)
#   4. **Programmatic API** (also
#     importable as a library; pino-pretty
#     library exports a transform for
#     in-process use)
#   5. **Stream transformer** (when used
#     programmatically in Node services,
#     can be installed as a Pino
#     destination transform)
#
# Distinguishing features:
#   - **Canonical Pino tooling**
#     (maintained by the pinojs
#     organization alongside the Pino
#     library itself; reference
#     implementation)
#   - **Stream-friendly** (pipeline-
#     mode by default; suitable for
#     shell + Docker + Kubernetes log
#     pipelines)
#   - **Highly configurable** (~20+
#     flags + nested config keys for
#     fine-grained formatting
#     control)
#   - **Color customization**
#     (level-specific colors via
#     custom-colors + custom-levels)
#   - **Time format translation**
#     (--translateTime converts ISO
#     timestamps + epoch ms to
#     human-readable formats)
#   - **Field filtering** (--ignore +
#     --include for hiding/showing
#     specific fields)
#
# Use cases:
#   - Development log viewing (Node
#     service logs in IDE terminal +
#     iTerm + Alacritty + ...)
#   - Local debugging (kubectl logs
#     pod | pino-pretty for
#     readable Kubernetes pod logs)
#   - CI/CD log review (pretty-print
#     CI step logs for human review)
#   - Stream-based real-time log
#     monitoring (docker logs -f
#     container | pino-pretty)
#   - Programmatic library use
#     (in-process pretty-printing in
#     Node CLI tools that produce
#     Pino logs)
#
# Usage:
#   cat app.log | pino-pretty
#   node app.js | pino-pretty
#   pino-pretty [options] < app.log
#
# Flags (minimist):
#   -c, --colorize                 - colorize
#                                     output
#                                     (auto-
#                                     detected
#                                     from
#                                     TTY)
#   -C                             - force
#                                     colorize
#                                     output
#                                     (even
#                                     when
#                                     not a
#                                     TTY)
#   -f, --crlf                     - use CRLF
#                                     line
#                                     endings
#                                     (Windows
#                                     compatibility)
#   -e, --errorProps <props>       - error
#                                     properties
#                                     to show
#                                     (default
#                                     all)
#   -l, --levelFirst               - show
#                                     level
#                                     as the
#                                     first
#                                     output
#                                     field
#   -L, --minimumLevel <level>     - minimum
#                                     log
#                                     level
#                                     to
#                                     display
#                                     (trace +
#                                     debug +
#                                     info +
#                                     warn +
#                                     error +
#                                     fatal +
#                                     silent)
#   -x, --customLevels <map>       - custom
#                                     level
#                                     mapping
#                                     (e.g.
#                                     "verbose:
#                                     35,
#                                     fatal:
#                                     70")
#   -X, --customColors <map>       - custom
#                                     level
#                                     colors
#                                     (e.g.
#                                     "fatal:
#                                     bgRed")
#   -U, --useOnlyCustomProps       - only
#                                     use
#                                     custom-
#                                     defined
#                                     levels
#                                     (suppress
#                                     defaults)
#   -k, --errorLikeObjectKeys <keys> - keys
#                                     that
#                                     contain
#                                     error-
#                                     like
#                                     objects
#                                     to
#                                     special-
#                                     case
#                                     format
#                                     (default
#                                     "err,
#                                     error")
#   -m, --messageKey <key>         - message
#                                     key
#                                     name
#                                     (default
#                                     "msg")
#       --levelKey <key>           - level
#                                     key
#                                     name
#                                     (default
#                                     "level")
#   -b, --levelLabel <label>       - label
#                                     for
#                                     level
#                                     output
#   -o, --messageFormat <fmt>      - custom
#                                     message
#                                     format
#                                     template
#                                     (e.g.
#                                     "{levelLabel}
#                                     -
#                                     {pid}
#                                     -
#                                     url:
#                                     {req.
#                                     url}")
#   -a, --timestampKey <key>       - timestamp
#                                     key
#                                     name
#                                     (default
#                                     "time")
#   -t, --translateTime <fmt>      - translate
#                                     timestamp
#                                     (true,
#                                     UTC,
#                                     "yyyy-
#                                     mm-dd",
#                                     SYS:
#                                     standard,
#                                     etc.)
#   -i, --ignore <keys>            - keys to
#                                     ignore
#                                     in
#                                     output
#                                     (comma-
#                                     separated)
#   -I, --include <keys>           - keys to
#                                     include
#                                     in
#                                     output
#                                     (comma-
#                                     separated;
#                                     mutually
#                                     exclusive
#                                     with
#                                     --ignore)
#   -H, --hideObject               - hide
#                                     object
#                                     from
#                                     output
#                                     (just
#                                     show
#                                     message)
#   -S, --singleLine               - show
#                                     log
#                                     object
#                                     on
#                                     single
#                                     line
#                                     (no
#                                     pretty-
#                                     printed
#                                     JSON)
#       --config <file>            - config
#                                     file
#                                     path
#                                     (.pino-
#                                     prettyrc
#                                     + pino-
#                                     pretty
#                                     .config
#                                     .cjs +
#                                     pino-
#                                     pretty
#                                     .config
#                                     .js)
#   -h, --help                     - show
#                                     help
#   -v, --version                  - show
#                                     version
#
# Example invocations:
#   # Pretty-print logs from stdin
#   cat app.log | pino-pretty
#
#   # Pipeline from running Node app
#   node app.js | pino-pretty
#
#   # Colorize + translate timestamps
#   node app.js | pino-pretty -c -t
#
#   # Filter to info+ level
#   cat app.log | pino-pretty -L info
#
#   # Custom message format
#   cat app.log | pino-pretty \
#     -o "{levelLabel} | {pid} | {hostname} | {msg}"
#
#   # Hide noisy fields
#   cat app.log | pino-pretty \
#     --ignore "pid,hostname,reqId"
#
#   # Show only specific fields
#   cat app.log | pino-pretty \
#     --include "time,level,msg,reqId"
#
#   # Single-line output (good for grep)
#   cat app.log | pino-pretty -S
#
#   # Single-line + translate time
#   docker logs container | \
#     pino-pretty -S -t
#
#   # Kubernetes pod logs
#   kubectl logs my-pod | pino-pretty -c -t
#
#   # Force colorize for CI logs
#   cat ci.log | pino-pretty -C
#
#   # Custom config file
#   pino-pretty --config ./my-config.cjs
#
# Configuration file (.pino-prettyrc):
#   ```json
#   {
#     "colorize": true,
#     "translateTime": "SYS:HH:MM:ss.l",
#     "messageFormat": "[{pid}] {levelLabel}: {msg}",
#     "ignore": "pid,hostname",
#     "singleLine": false,
#     "minimumLevel": "info",
#     "errorLikeObjectKeys": ["err", "error", "cause"]
#   }
#   ```
#
# Or as JavaScript (.pino-prettyrc.cjs):
#   ```javascript
#   module.exports = {
#     colorize: true,
#     translateTime: 'SYS:standard',
#     ignore: ['pid', 'hostname']
#   };
#   ```
#
# The pino-pretty CLI is the official
# tooling shipped by the pinojs
# organization to pair with the Pino
# logger library. Both are maintained
# under the same GitHub org.
#
# pinojs/pino is the de-facto canonical
# Node structured logging library:
#   - **Extreme performance** (Pino is
#     consistently the fastest Node
#     logger in benchmarks; ~5-10x
#     faster than Winston + Bunyan)
#   - **JSON-first design** (logs emit
#     as JSON by default for log-
#     aggregator consumption; pino-
#     pretty handles dev formatting
#     separately)
#   - **Async + non-blocking** (uses
#     a separate worker thread for log
#     writes; doesn't block the main
#     event loop)
#   - **Child loggers** (clone parent
#     logger + add fixed fields per-
#     scope; canonical pattern for
#     HTTP request-scoped logging)
#   - **Stream-based transports**
#     (pino-pretty + pino-elasticsearch
#     + pino-mongodb + pino-loki +
#     ... all are pluggable Pino
#     destinations)
#   - **Used by Fastify** (Fastify's
#     official logger; Fastify is the
#     fastest Node web framework +
#     Pino is its default logger)
#   - **~25,000,000 weekly npm
#     downloads as `pino` package**
